title: For Sale:  Graham Defense BCG (yes it IS gold)
postcontent: Hey folks I am letting go of a Top Quality Competition BCG manufactured by Graham Defense. The reason this BCG is gold in color is due to the Finish. It's called Titanium Nitride (TiN), and is one step above Nickle Boron (NiB) in both price and durabillity. TiN has a little less Lubricity than NiB but lasts longer and also handles higher heat MUCH better. I am going to list several of the BCG finishes in order from cheapest and highest wear-rate to most expensive and lowest wear-rate. Hard Chrome: the military used this for a while because the chrome had a natural lubricity characteristic which allowed the bolt to run very smooth. However, the chrome finish would begin to flake off the bolt would lose that desired "smoothness."Phosphate: These BCG's are by far the most popular on the market and the most cost efficient. They are the current military standard due to High Durability. But just being "Mil-Spec" doesn't mean that it holds ALL of the best characteristics. It's primary advantage is high durability, but being that it doesn't have a very smooth finish, the action will have a more noticeable "grind" and drag to it and it will also increase chamber temperatures. These bolts are also VERY tough to clean and the outer finish is rough.Black Nitride: This treament is one step above Phosphate because it sports a glossy finish and is more wear-resistent. It is more common with barrels so as to improve barrel life, and is much easier to clean than Parkerized treatments used on the Phosphate BCG's.Nickel Boron (NiB): This finish is highly desired amongst the tactical scene as it looks good in any rifle build, is highly lubricious, and is extremely easy to clean. It's drawbacks though, are that the coating becomes dicolored (gets daker and looses luster) after moderate use, and will eventually flake off reducing some of its lubricious qualities.Titanium Nitride (TiN): This treament can in some cases be one of the more expensive options (but not always the MOST) when is comes to buying a High-End BCG. Its main perks are that it is Highly wear-resistent, can stand up to extreme temperatures (moreso than the former options listed), and is Highly Lubricious. This treament does NOT become discolored after use like the Nickle Boron varieties. The only option on the market that Beats the TiN treatment in Lubricity is the NP3 (Electroless Nickle) treatment, often confused with Nickle Boron. NP3 is a metal treatment and NOT a coating wich Allows it to maintain high lubricity. However, NP3 BCG's tend to be the MOST expensive on the market. These are not "opinions" people, these are Studies and Scientific Facts, so please Spare me your "Hate Mail" claiming that phosphate is the "best" on the market. People want differemt products for different reasons, these are merely the Factual properties of each option.I WILL advise against having the TiN treament done to an existing BCG, though. Simply becasue the ones that come from the factory are made to diffferent dimensional specifications that allow extra room for the thick outer treament. The factory TiN BCG's are also comprised of alloyed steel that bonds properly with the TiN treatement, eliminating the flaking that happens with other coatings.If you get a phosphate bcg aftermarket caoted, you will most likely not experince the smoother lubricity as you have added a layer of extra material making the fitment inside the upper receiver MUCH tighter, wich will ultimately slow the action and wear the new BCG coating as well as the inside of your upper receiver. You definitely do not want that. Aaaaaaaaaaaaaaalrighty then, let's get down to the nitty-gritty. My BCG here has seen and properly ran 300 rounds. Graham Defense does NOT mass produce a SINGLE item and carefully precision machines and thuroughly inspects ALL of their items before giving them the stamp of approval. Everything they manufacture is built for Competition conditions where Failure is NOT an option. Think of this Awesome BCG as fine Small batch whisky. You Certainly get what you pay for when it comes this guy and quite honestly, most things in life.My price is $160 FIRM as these retail for $225 + shipping. I will NOT take less. I am not looking to trade at this time. if youre interested, please feel free to message me night or day. REDACTED
